               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Gregorian" notAfter="1450" notBefore="1425">15th century, second quarter</origDate>
                     <origPlace>
                        <country key="place_7024097">Flanders</country>, <settlement key="place_7008002">Tournai</settlement>
                        <!--ORIGINAL: Flemish, Tournai-->
                     </origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  
                  <provenance>The occurrence of 'Saint Lehyre' (Eleutherius, 20 February) in red, and S. Piat (1 October) in the Calendar in red, and in the Litany, 
                     shows that the use is of Tournai. St Guislein also occurs on 9 October. St. Cierge (28 February) and St. Ladre (17 December) are unusual names ('Ladre' is 'Lazarus', traditionally 1st bishop 
                     of Marseille)</provenance>
                  
                  <provenance> In the calendar, the dedication of the cathedral of Notre-Dame is entered on 6 May</provenance>
                  
                  <provenance><persName key="person_2384880" role="fmo">Matteo Luigi Canonici (1727– <hi rend="italic">c</hi>. 1806)</persName></provenance>
                  <provenance notAfter="1807" resp="#SC">Following Canonici's death, the collection passed to his brother, <persName key="person_446" role="fmo">Giuseppe Canonici</persName>, and 
                     then to Canonici's nephew, <persName role="fmo" key="person_431">Giovanni Perissinotti</persName>, in 1807 following Giuseppe Canonici's death</provenance>
                  <acquisition when="1817">Bought by the Bodleian Library in 1817 from Giovanni Perissinotti. On the purchase, see <ref target="https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/collections/canonici/">Digital Bodleian</ref></acquisition>
                  
               </history>
               
